Introduction

This Student Performance Report is a quick Exploratory Data Analysis followed by some modeling that aims to predit student test scores from various variables in the dataset.

Part2

Cleaning

There are some spaces between some of the variables so let's clean that up a little bit. We also are going to need to convert a few variables such as gender and test.prep to dummy variables. Another intresting find would be to see if a student scored above or below the mean. To do this we create a few new variables that will let us know if a student scored above or below the mean test score. We will  finish off creating a few variables we will use later on in the report. 
names(data)[names(data) == "math score"] <- "math.score"
names(data)[names(data) == "writing score"] <- "writing.score"
names(data)[names(data) == "reading score"] <- "reading.score"
names(data)[names(data) == "parental level of education"] <- "parent.edu"
names(data)[names(data) == "testing preparation course"] <- "test.prep"
data1 <- dummy_cols(data, select_columns = c("test preparation course", "gender"))
reading.score.mean <- mean(data$reading.score)
math.score.mean <- mean(data$math.score)
writing.score.mean <- mean(data$math.score)
data  <- data %>% mutate(math.above.below = ifelse(math.score < math.score.mean, "Below Mean", "Above Mean"))
data  <- data %>% mutate(reading.above.below = ifelse(reading.score < reading.score.mean, "Below Mean", "Above Mean"))
data  <- data %>% mutate(writing.above.below = ifelse(writing.score < writing.score.mean, "Below Mean", "Above Mean"))

Counts are a good way of explaining data numerically, but they are not always the funniest thing to scroll through. We are going to create a few graphs which should make viewing counts or the distribution of the data easier. Before we get to the graphs, let's get the correlation between the test scores.

Correlation

data %>% summarize(N = n(), r = cor(math.score, reading.score))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##       N     r
##   <int> <dbl>
## 1  1000 0.818
data %>% summarize(N = n(), r = cor(math.score, writing.score))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##       N     r
##   <int> <dbl>
## 1  1000 0.803
data %>% summarize(N = n(), r = cor(reading.score, writing.score))
## # A tibble: 1 x 2
##       N     r
##   <int> <dbl>
## 1  1000 0.955
The correlation  between all the variables are above .8 which is a very high correlation. The correlation between reading and writing is the hightest of all variables at 0.9545981. It appears if you score well on one test, you should do well on all the others as well. The inverse is true as well, as test scores decrease in one subject they tend to decrease in other subjects.

I wonder if we have students who performed well on one test, but did not so well on another. Lets look through the dataset and see if we can find such student. We also can also do a few other filter options that we will add to the code.

Part4

Graphs

Graphs are a great way to visualize data and a way to visualize the numerical data you have been working with. I created a few graphs to do just that.

Scatter

options(repr.plot.width = 5, repr.plot.height = 4)
ggplot(data, aes(x = writing.score, y = reading.score)) + geom_point() + geom_jitter() + labs(x = "Writing Score", y = "Reading Score")

ggplot(data, aes(x = writing.score, y = reading.score)) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~ gender)

ggplot(data, aes(x = writing.score, y = math.score)) + geom_point() + labs(x = "Writing Score", y = "Math Score") + facet_wrap(~ gender)

ggplot(data, aes(x = reading.score, y = math.score)) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~ gender)

Bar

ggplot(data, aes(x = parent.edu)) + geom_bar() + coord_flip()

part5

Models

The models I created aimss to predict math score and writing score, the dependent variables, from a variety of independent variables which include: gender, other scores, race, parent education, and test preparation course.  Regression models formula are written as: 
Y = a + bX + e_i where Y = dependent variable, a is the intercept, b is the coefficient, X is the independent variable, and e_i is the error term. Once we have the model we can place the coefficients with the independent variables inside the model to predict our dependent variable. We will conclude with a summary of our models and a quick conclusion.
model <- lm(math.score ~ gender_female + writing.score + reading.score + `test preparation course_completed`, data = data1)
model1.2 <- lm(math.score ~ gender_female + writing.score + reading.score + `test preparation course_none`, data = data1)
model2 <- lm(math.score ~ gender_male + writing.score + reading.score + `test preparation course_completed`, data = data1)
model2.2 <- lm(math.score ~ gender_male + writing.score + reading.score + `test preparation course_none`, data = data1)
model3 <- lm(math.score ~ gender_male + writing.score + reading.score + `test preparation course_none` + parent.edu + `race/ethnicity` , data = data1)
model4 <-  lm(math.score ~ gender_female + writing.score + reading.score + `test preparation course_completed` + parent.edu + `race/ethnicity` , data = data1)
model5 <- lm(writing.score ~ gender_female + math.score + parent.edu + `test preparation course_none`, data = data1)

part6

Conclusion

We started this R project with a question. The question was, can we predict student test scores from variables within the dataset? before we could began the project we had to load a few libraries into R. After loading in our data, we did a little tidying before exploring our data more in depth. We took counts by gender, found a few outliers, and found the correlation between a few of our variables. Graphs were created to visualize some of our data and make it easy for anyone to understand the distribution of our data. We concluded the project with some modeling to answer our question of predicting student test scores.
